1️⃣ CSR vs SSR vs SSG

This is one of the most important senior-level frontend topics.


---

🔵 CSR (Client-Side Rendering)

How it works:

Browser → Download JS → Render React → Fetch API → Update UI

Example:

useEffect(() => {
  fetch("/api/products")
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(setProducts);
}, []);

✅ Pros:

Fast navigation after first load

Great for dashboards

Less server load


❌ Cons:

Poor SEO

Slow first paint

Blank screen before JS loads


When to use:

Internal admin dashboards

Authenticated apps



---

🟢 SSR (Server-Side Rendering)

Server renders HTML on each request.

Browser → Request → Server renders HTML → Send ready HTML

Example (Next.js):

export async function getServerSideProps() {
  const res = await fetch("https://api.example.com/products");
  const products = await res.json();
  return { props: { products } };
}

✅ Pros:

Better SEO

Faster first paint

Good for dynamic content


❌ Cons:

Higher server cost

Slower TTFB

Harder caching


When to use:

E-commerce product pages

SEO-heavy apps



---

🟣 SSG (Static Site Generation)

Pages generated at build time.

Build Time → Pre-render HTML → CDN serves static page

Example:

export async function getStaticProps() {
  const data = await fetchProducts();
  return { props: { data } };
}

✅ Pros:

Extremely fast

Cheap hosting

CDN-friendly

Great SEO


❌ Cons:

Not ideal for real-time data

Requires rebuild for updates


When to use:

Blogs

Marketing pages

Documentation



---

🎯 Senior Interview Insight

Say this:

> “I choose rendering strategy based on content volatility and SEO requirements.”



That’s senior-level thinking.


