2️⃣ Code Splitting

Large React bundles slow initial load.

Problem:

Entire JS bundle loads at once.

Solution:

Split into smaller chunks.

Example:

const AdminPanel = React.lazy(() => import("./AdminPanel"));

Benefits:

Faster initial load

Reduced Time to Interactive

Better performance on low-end devices


In production: Webpack automatically splits chunks.


---

3️⃣ Lazy Loading

Load components only when needed.

Example:

import React, { Suspense } from "react";

const HeavyComponent = React.lazy(() => import("./HeavyComponent"));

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
      <HeavyComponent />
    </Suspense>
  );
}

Use cases:

Large charts

Modals

Admin routes


Senior Tip: Lazy load routes, not small UI components.


---

4️⃣ Hydration

Hydration = Attaching React to server-rendered HTML.

In SSR:

1. Server sends pre-rendered HTML.


2. Browser downloads JS.


3. React "hydrates" and attaches event listeners.



Process:

HTML (static) → React JS loads → React attaches listeners

Problem: Hydration mismatch if server and client render different HTML.

Fix: Avoid using browser-only APIs during SSR.

Example:

if (typeof window !== "undefined") {
  // Safe client code
}

Senior Insight: Hydration is CPU-expensive on large pages.


---

5️⃣ Performance Optimization

Senior-level focus areas:


---

🔹 1. Avoid Unnecessary Re-renders

Common mistake: State placed too high in component tree.

Fix: Move state closer to where it's needed.


---

🔹 2. Key Prop Optimization

Wrong:

{items.map((item, index) => (
  <div key={index}>{item.name}</div>
))}

Correct:

{items.map((item) => (
  <div key={item.id}>{item.name}</div>
))}


---

🔹 3. Use React Profiler

Measure:

Commit time

Re-render frequency



---

🔹 4. Virtualization for Large Lists

Use libraries like:

react-window

react-virtualized


Renders only visible rows.


---

6️⃣ Memoization

Used to prevent expensive recalculations.


---

useMemo

const sortedItems = useMemo(() => {
  return items.sort((a, b) => a.price - b.price);
}, [items]);

Prevents recalculating on every render.


---

useCallback

const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
  console.log("Clicked");
}, []);

Prevents recreating functions unnecessarily.


---

React.memo

const ProductCard = React.memo(({ product }) => {
  return <div>{product.name}</div>;
});

Prevents re-render if props unchanged.


---

Senior Warning:

Overusing memoization can reduce performance.

Use only when necessary.


